      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(providers): release stream reader lock after classifying SDK stream body",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n`src/agents/provider-transport-fetch.ts:349` acquires a `ReadableStream` reader via `response.body?.getReader()` in `classifyOpenAISdkStreamBody` but does not call `reader.releaseLock()` in the finally block. If the classification throws, the reader lock is leaked.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `src/agents/provider-transport-fetch.ts`: add `reader.releaseLock()` (wrapped in try/catch) in the finally block after `reader.cancel()`\n\nThis matches the defensive lock-release pattern used elsewhere in the codebase.\n\nLabel: bugfix | merge-risk: 🟢 minimal | AI-assisted\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Code path analysis\n\nThe affected function `classifyOpenAISdkStreamBody`:\n1. Acquires `reader = response.body?.getReader()`\n2. Reads the first chunk to classify the stream type\n3. Has a `finally` block that calls `reader.cancel()` but did NOT call `reader.releaseLock()`\n\n`reader.cancel()` rejects pending reads but does not release the lock on the underlying stream. Per the Streams specification, `releaseLock()` is required to allow other consumers to acquire the stream. Adding it ensures proper cleanup.",
        "branch": "fix/provider-classify-stream-reader-release",
